A deed ‘in modo indenture' so called because its upper margin was indented, so that being prepared and cut in duplicate, the two parts when brought together at any subsequent period could then afford proof of their common origin. The word ‘Indenture' was also written across the indentations.

Sometimes the deed was called a ‘cyrograph‚’ that being the word written.
